                <div class="kicker"><span class="kicker"><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/news">NEWS</a></span></div>

                <h1>First California, now Japan: The longest roads to healing</h1>
                
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/jason-greenwald">Jason Greenwald</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">January 25, 1995 | 12:00am EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/1995/01/first-california-now-japan-longest-roads-healing" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/1995/01/first-california-now-japan-longest-roads-healing&amp;text=First California, now Japan: The longest roads to healing" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=First%20California%2C%20now%20Japan%3A%20The%20longest%20roads%20to%20healing%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F1995%2F01%2Ffirst-california-now-japan-longest-roads-healing" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Los Angeles. Another disaster strikes, and immediately we assess the numbers: 7.2 magnitude, $20 billion in damage, 600 dead... 1,700... 3,000... and counting.</p>
<p>A powerful earthquake has shaken Japan, and now we're glued to CNN: We survey the wreckage and try to quantify the misery. For those of us in California, Kobe is a stunning reminder of Northridge, the quake that struck exactly one year earlier.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>I shudder as I think about the dreadful process Japan is now beginning. Aftershocks. Broken buildings. Lack of water and power. A road to recovery, stretching for months or years.</p>
<p>In my own recollection, last Jan. 17 is yesterday. Even after a year of rebuilding, I can recall those early morning hours in precise detail. The initial jolt, which shook me from my bed. The realization of danger, which spurred me to action. The sense, only much later, of tremendous loss. Amid the visions of fright, sadness and relief, I also remember the numbers.</p>
<p>Minutes after the Northridge quake, a frenzied neighbor knocked on my door. &quot;How big was it?&quot; he demanded. Before I could answer, he added, &quot;It must've been an eight.&quot; As in magnitude 8.0, what the experts call a &quot;great&quot; quake--or simply the Big One.</p>
<p>As damage estimates soared, I, too, relied on the numbers. If this earthquake was going to cost up to $30 billion, if this earthquake was going to be the most expensive natural disaster in American history, then surely I was justified in my sense of loss.</p>
<p>Later, the magnitude was said to be 6.7. The damage estimate was lowered to $20 billion.</p>
<p>Did these figures invalidate our emotions?</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Last Tuesday, as I pondered Northridge and Kobe, I realized that numbers can never tell us the real story of disaster. Does the actual size or cost of a disaster really matter? It is, I suppose, only natural to try to measure our grief. After all, if we can quantify, we can hope to understand. But human emotions are not so simple, and tragedy cannot be quantified.</p>
<p>If your home is a pile of rubble, it probably doesn't matter whether the overall damage is in millions or billions.</p>
<p>If you've lost a loved one, the magnitude of an earthquake is irrelevant.</p>
<p>Thousands of people die every day in this country, yet we hardly ever take notice. Why, then, do we mourn large-scale tragedy? Because it seems less predictable? Because it overwhelms us? Because we have an attachment to a particular place or people?</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
                    <input type="hidden" value="1" name="group[29][1]" id="mce-group[29]-29-0">

                    <div class="input-group-append">
                        <input type="submit" value="Subscribe" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm sends-events" data-ga-category="CTA" data-ga-action="email_focus" data-ga-label="c4087a59c7" />
                    </div>
