                <div style="position: absolute; left: -5000px;"><input type="text" name="b_c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b_c4087a59c7" tabindex="-1" value=""></div>

            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Tuesday morning, these questions swirled in my mind. At the fateful hour of 4:31 a.m., when one year earlier the earth shook beneath us, I stood on a cold windy sidewalk with 500 strangers.</p>
<p>We joined together--people of all faiths and backgrounds--to share in our remembrance of last January 17.</p>
<p>Some people had been able to heal their emotional scars quickly. Others were still torn apart.</p>
<p>Some, like me, wanted long ago to believe that we had conquered our fears, only later to find that we hadn't.</p>
<p>Two weeks after the earthquake, I decided that it was time to put my angst behind me. That was fine, except that I would later spend a month living in a hotel during repairs to my home. Even now, the sound of hammers emanates from next door. On one corner of my block, all four apartment complexes are surrounded by chain link fences. They are in varying stages of repair; rubble is piled on the edges of the street.</p>
<p>With so many reminders, it's been hard to move forward. For the most part, I'd been successful--until last Sunday. On that night I hardly slept. It was the night before the day before the anniversary and it brought back every fear I'd felt for the past twelve months.</p>
<p>I wondered if I was falling back into fright.</p>
<p>In the four o'clock hour of Tuesday morning, though, I didn't feel any of these concerns. I was saddened by the thought of those who died and my thoughts turned also to Japan.</p>

                                                    <div class="related my-4 py-4 d-print-none">
